'''Ixtlilton''' ({{lang-nah|Ixtlilton}} {{IPA-nah|iʃˈtɬiɬton|pron}},''The Little Black One'') in [[aztec mythology]] is the [[Deity|god]] of medicine and healing,<ref>{{cite book|title=Diccionario de Mitología Nahua|editor=Biblioteca Porrúa. Imprenta del Museo Nacional de Arqueología, Historia y Etnología|authorlink=Cecilio Agustín Robelo|language=Spanish|year=1905|location=México|pages=217, 218|isbn=978-9684327955}}</ref> and therefore was often alluded to as the brother of [[Macuilxochitl]]{{citation needed|date=June 2013}}, the god of well-being or good luck. Ixtlilton was a gentle god, who emanated from an [[obsidian]] mask which brought darkness and peaceful sleep to children in their beds at night.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ambergriscaye.com/pages/mayan/aztecreligion-minordeities.html|title=Aztec Religion - AZTEC GODS - Aztecs of Mexico History|website=ambergriscaye.com}}</ref>

